messages.content:
Based on the following question, analyze it carefully and provide your probability estimate.

Question: Will either metac-GPT4o or metac-o1 finish with a rank between 10 and 25 inclusive in the Q1 2025 Quarterly Cup?
Background: Each quarter, Metaculus runs a short tournament called [the Quarterly Cup](https://www.metaculus.com/tournament/32630/), which consists of 40-50 questions on various topics. Quarterly Cups have been some of the most popular tournaments on the site with hundreds of users forecasting on at least one tournament question in each quarter. In Q3 2024, Metaculus launched the [AI Forecasting Benchmark Tournament series](https://www.metaculus.com/notebooks/25525/openai-anthropic-donate-credits-for-ai-forecasting-benchmark-tournament-asknews-provides-free-news-source/), which compares bots on forecasting questions. Bots are also allowed to forecast in other questions too (although they are not included in the Community Prediction) and currently Metaculus has two bots compete in the Quarterly Cup: metac-GPT4o and metac-o1.

Both bots consist of a combination of a GPT model and AskNews for search. Both forecast every two days, using the same basic prompt (example for binary questions):

> You are a professional forecaster interviewing for a job.Your interview question is:
> \{title}
> â€Ž
> Question background:
> \{background}
> â€Ž
> This question's outcome will be determined by the specific criteria below. These criteria have not yet been satisfied:
> \{resolution\_criteria}
> \{fine\_print}
> â€Ž
> Your research assistant says:
> \{summary\_report}
> â€Ž
> Today is
> \{today}.
> â€Ž
> Before answering you write:
> (a) The time left until the outcome to the question is known.
> (b) The status quo outcome if nothing changed.
> (c) A brief description of a scenario that results in a No outcome.
> (d) A brief description of a scenario that results in a Yes outcome.
> â€Ž
> You write your rationale remembering that good forecasters put extra weight on the status quo outcome since the world changes slowly most of the time.
> â€Ž
> The last thing you write is your final answer as: "Probability: ZZ%", 0-100

with the prompt for AskNews being

> You are an assistant to a superforecaster. The superforecaster will give you a question they intend to forecast on. To be a great assistant, you generate a concise but detailed rundown of the most relevant news, including if the question would resolve Yes or No based on current information. You do not produce forecasts yourself.
>
> Note that bots do not affect forecaster ranks or scores in any way.
Resolution criteria: This question will resolve as YES if either metac-GPT4o or metac-o1 finish with a rank between 10 and 25 inclusive in the Q1 2025 Quarterly Cup Leaderboard after all questions besides this one have been resolved and no more questions are set to open. Otherwise, it will resolve as NO.
Fine print: The bots might disappear from the tournament leaderboard after a question has resolved. Please tag me (@skmmcj) somewhere to make them appear again.

messages.content:
Based on the extracted evidence from the Metaculus page regarding the Q1 2025 Quarterly Cup, the community prediction for the highest rank of either metac-GPT4o or metac-o1 is as follows:

1. **Community Prediction Median**: 29.61
2. **Lower 25% Quartile**: 11.69
3. **Upper 75% Quartile**: 75.72

The community prediction indicates that there is a reasonable probability that either metac-GPT4o or metac-o1 could finish with a rank between 10 and 25. Specifically, the lower quartile of the prediction is 11.69, which falls within the target range of 10 to 25. This suggests that there is at least a 25% probability that one of the bots will achieve a rank within this range.

Given this information, along with the fact that the median prediction is 29.61, which is not far from the upper bound of the target range, I would estimate the probability of the event occurring (either bot finishing between rank 10 and 25) to be slightly higher than the lower quartile probability, considering the distribution and the nature of forecasting tournaments where performance can vary significantly.

FINAL PROBABILITY: 0.35
